label.value: normal initial meiotic spindle pole body separation in meiosis I

definition.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the initial release of duplicated spindle pole bodies that occurs as part of the first meiotic nuclear division, is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: decreased rate of cytoplasmic microtubule polymerization during mitotic interphase

value.value: A microtubule cytoskeleton organization phenotype observed during mitotic interphase in which cytoplasmic microtubule polymerization, i.e. the addition of tubulin dimers to the plus end of a microtubule occurs at a lower rate, or speed, than normal.

label.value: decreased duration of cytoplasmic microtubule growth events during mitotic interphase

value.value: A microtubule cytoskeleton organization phenotype observed during mitotic interphase in which the duration of cytoplasmic microtubule growth events is shorter.

label.value: increased mitochondrial-associated microtubule fraction during mitotic interphase

value.value: A mitochondrion distribution phenotype observed during mitotic interphase in which the length fraction of cytoplasmic microtubules that is bound to mitochondria is increased with respect to the wild type.

label.value: abolished nuclear fusion with normal nuclear congression during mating

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which karyogamy involved in conjugation with cellular fusion does not occur, despite the nuclei and their SPBs coming together.

label.value: horsetail movement with unfused nuclei

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which horsetail movement occurs without nuclei fusing. This can happen with both nuclei having congressed and their SPBs having coalesced, but nuclei having failed to fuse, see PMID:36650056.

label.value: increased interphase nuclear movement velocity in daughter cell without mitochondria

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in mitotic interphase in which microtubule-based movement oscillations occur at a faster speed than normal in a daughter cell that inherits no mitochondria.

label.value: abnormal meiotic cell cycle entry

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which a cell enters the meiotic cell cycle without either of the normal steps that precede it: conjugation with cellular fusion and karyogamy with nuclear fusion.

label.value: decreased vegetative cell population viability

value.value: A vegetative cell population phenotype in which a lower than normal proportion of cells is viable. In High Throughput Phenotyping this is typically assessed using phloxine as a dye.
Not to be confused with cell population growth phenotypes, which are measured with culture density or by serial dilution on solid medium.

label.value: increased vegetative cell population viability

value.value: A vegetative cell population phenotype in which a larger than normal proportion of cells is viable. In High Throughput Phenotyping this is typically assessed using phloxine as a dye.
Not to be confused with cell population growth phenotypes, which are measured with culture density or by serial dilution on solid medium.

label.value: decreased cell population growth on arginine nitrogen source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cell growth is decreased relative to normal in a medium containing arginine as the nitrogen source.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

label.value: resistance to UV during vegetative growth

definition.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased resistance to ultraviolet light.

label.value: increased cell population viability on galactose carbon source

definition.value: A vegetative cell population phenotype in which a larger than normal proportion of cells is viable when grown with galactose as carbon source. In High Throughput Phenotyping this is typically assessed using phloxine as a dye.
Not to be confused with cell population growth phenotypes, which are measured with culture density or by serial dilution on solid medium.

label.value: decreased vegetative cell population viability on galactose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population phenotype in which a lower than normal proportion of cells is viable when the medium contains galactose as carbon source. In High Throughput Phenotyping this is typically assessed using phloxine as a dye.

label.value: decreased vegetative cell population viability on glycerol carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population phenotype in which a lower than normal proportion of cells is viable when the medium contains glycerol as carbon source. In High Throughput Phenotyping this is typically assessed using phloxine as a dye.

label.value: increased cell population viability on glycerol carbon source

definition.value: A vegetative cell population phenotype in which a larger than normal proportion of cells is viable when grown with glycerol as carbon source. In High Throughput Phenotyping this is typically assessed using phloxine as a dye.

label.value: reduced viability in stationary phase upon glucose starvation in the presence of cadmium

definition.value: A cell population phenotype in which a smaller than normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable after entering stationary phase, when subjected to glucose starvation and when cadmium is present in the medium in a higher proportion than usual.

label.value: increased viability in stationary phase upon glucose starvation in the presence of cadmium

definition.value: A cell population phenotype in which a higher than normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable after entering stationary phase, when subjected to glucose starvation and when cadmium is present in the medium in a higher proportion than usual.

label.value: increased vegetative cell population binucleate index

value.value: A vegetative cell population phenotype in which the poportion of cells with two nuclei is higher than normal.

label.value: decreased vegetative cell population binucleate index

value.value: A vegetative cell population phenotype in which the poportion of cells with two nuclei is lower than normal.
